And we love it!   We think it's cozy and comfy.  But it may not be for everyone. description: Spacious Bed-Stuy modern studio located 5-10 mins from A, C, & G trains. Queen-sized bed, and a pullout daybed that can accommodate two more people! Great location for aforementioned train access, along with a plethora of nearby dining options. It borders Williamsburg to the north at Flushing Avenue and Crown Heights to the south at Fulton Street, and spans from Bedford Avenue to Broadway. One of Brooklyn’s oldest established neighborhoods, it can be a great alternative to the more expensive Brooklyn neighborhoods closer to Manhattan, with a charm all its own. Built around what was once a central train station and is now an outpost of the Long Island Rail Road, Bedford-Stuyvesant has been best known as an African-American cultural hub, a counterpart to Manhattan’s Harlem. One of Bed-Stuy’s trademarks is as a setting and inspiration for Spike Lee’s movies, including Do the Right Thing, and the neighborhood will look familiar to fans of the film. Mos Def, the Notorious B.I.G., Chris Rock
name: Bed Stuy Home Away From Home

description: Located on the corner of Dartmouth & Newbury Streets in the Back Bay, this historic 1 bed/1 bath is the perfect apartment for anyone who craves the excitement of city living. A half-block from the Boston Marathon finish line & steps from the subway. Originally built in 1886 as the Hotel Victoria, the building is considered one of Boston’s few examples of “Exotic Revivals” which is the grouping given to Victorian architects who sought inspiration in remote locations. Designed by John Faxon as an example of Moorish Revival, the building in the heart of Copley Square has lent a cosmopolitan flair to the city’s Back Bay neighborhood for over a hundred years.  The apartment was originally a part of the Hotel Victoria’s lobby. The intricate flooring in the living room has been fixed as best able, and the original stained glass windows were restored in 2006 after they had begun to buckle from the passage of time; they are the only original stained glass windows that remain in the building tod
name: Boston Back Bay/Copley Square

The bright windows, the old style kitchen inventory, the long dining table, the view to the tomato plants on the fire escape, the sounds of birds in the back yard... It's just really nice to be here. The apartment has an open railroad layout with the living room in the other end of the apartment. In between kitchen and living room there's a bed room and a room with closets. Our apartment is very personally furnished with both old and new stuff from  Scandinavia and the United States.  It's located on a quiet tree lined street, a block from restaurants and bars, shopping and subway. We will be reachable by phone, text or email any time. Carroll Gardens is for guests who want to explore
name: Cosy apartment in Carroll Gardens

description: Beautiful loft located on lower Nob Hill.  Cable car, Union Square and the Wharf are within walking distance.  Great international restaurants, shopping and theaters close by.    There is a private garage, and the house has easy access to Marin and Chrissy Field. This is a brick building from 1914 that has been updated for the 21st Century.  This property was home to renowned interior designer Robert Hutchinson for nearly 50 years.  Mr. Hutchinson bought the property in 1961 and turned the first floor into his studio, while he lived upstairs.  The second story, where you will be staying, has seen many designs over the years.  Once, it was Chinese red, another time it was black.  When it was featured in Architectural Digest in 1986, the walls and ceilings were tan and the flat was filled with tribal art from around the globe.
